  "prompt": "So, can a sentence begin with the word \"so\"?",
  "response": "Yes, a sentence can definitely begin with the word \"so.\"\n\nWhile some grammar sticklers used to discourage it, starting a sentence with \"so\" is perfectly acceptable in modern English and is commonly used. It can function in a few different ways:\n\n*   **As a conjunction:** To indicate a consequence, result, or conclusion. Example: \"The store was closed, so we went home.\"\n*   **As an introductory word to set the stage or transition to a new topic:** Example: \"So, how was your day?\"\n*   **As an interjection:** To express surprise, understanding, or agreement. Example: \"So! You finally finished the project.\"\n\nUltimately, whether or not to start a sentence with \"so\" is a matter of style and context. Overuse can be repetitive, but in moderation, it's a perfectly valid way to begin a sentence.\n",
